<Layout title="Webhook Security: How to Secure Your Endpoints — Rupadana">
  <article class="reveal">
    <span class="tag">Security</span>
    <h1>Webhook Security: How to Secure Your Endpoints</h1>
    <div class="meta">Moving beyond simple endpoints: How to verify, protect, and harden your webhooks.</div>

    <div class="card article-content">
      <p>
        Webhooks are the glue of the modern web, allowing services like Stripe, GitHub, and 
        Shopify to notify your application when something happens. But there’s a catch: 
        a webhook endpoint is a publicly accessible URL. If you don't secure it, anyone 
        can send fake data to your server, triggering unauthorized actions or corrupting your database.
      </p>

      <div class="callout">
        Webhook security is about answering one critical question: <strong>"How do I know this 
        request actually came from the service I trust?"</strong>
      </div>

      <h2>1. Payload Signature Verification (HMAC)</h2>
      <p>
        This is the gold standard for webhook security. Most reputable providers (Stripe, GitHub, etc.) 
        will sign the payload using a secret key only you and the provider know.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>The provider hashes the payload with the secret key and sends the hash in a header (e.g., <code>X-Hub-Signature</code>).</li>
        <li>Your server computes the hash of the received payload using the same secret.</li>
        <li>If the hashes match, the request is authentic and the data hasn't been tampered with.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>2. Replay Attack Protection</h2>
      <p>
        An attacker could intercept a valid signed request and send it again (a replay attack). 
        To prevent this, many providers include a timestamp in the signature header. 
        Your server should check if the timestamp is recent (e.g., within the last 5 minutes) 
        before processing the request.
      </p>

      <h2>3. IP Allowlisting</h2>
      <p>
        Some providers publish a list of IP addresses they use to send webhooks. You can 
        configure your firewall or application to only accept requests from these IPs. 
        While not sufficient on its own (IPs can be spoofed), it adds a solid layer of defense-in-depth.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Secret Tokens</h2>
      <p>
        A simpler (but less robust) method is to include a unique secret token in the webhook URL 
        or as a header. Your server checks for this token before processing. 
        Example: <code>https://your-api.com/webhooks?token=SECRET_VALUE</code>. 
        Note: This doesn't prevent payload tampering, but it stops random bots from hitting your endpoint.
      </p>

      <h2>5. Idempotency (Again!)</h2>
      <p>
        As we discussed in the previous post, webhooks are often delivered "at-least-once." 
        Your webhook handler <strong>must</strong> be idempotent. If you receive the same 
        event ID twice, your system should recognize it and avoid performing the same 
        action twice (like double-shipping an order).
      </p>

      <h2>6. HTTPS is Mandatory</h2>
      <p>
        Never use HTTP for webhooks. Without TLS encryption, your secrets, tokens, and 
        payload data are sent in plain text across the internet, making them trivial 
        to intercept.
      </p>

      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>
        Securing webhooks is not just about keeping hackers out; it's about system 
        predictability. By implementing signature verification and idempotency, 
        you ensure that your integrations are both secure and resilient to the 
        chaos of the public internet.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

